{"cursor":"11205","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"'Spontaneous emission' is the process by which a light source such as an atom,\nmolecule, nanocrystal or nucleus in an excited state undergoes a transition to a\nstate with a lower energy, e.g., the ground state and emits a photon.\nSpontaneous emission of light or luminescence is a fundamental process that\nplays an essential role in many phenomena in nature and forms the basis of many\napplications, such as fluorescent tubes, older television screens (cathode ray\ntubes), plasma display panels, lasers (for startup - normal continuous operation\nworks by stimulated emission instead) and light emitting diodes.\n","linknr":214,"url":"Spontaneous_emission","recorded":1362675940,"links":30,"instances":["waves","optics"],"pdf":["http://cops.tnw.utwente.nl/pdf/05/PHYSICAL%20REVIEW%20LETTERS%2095%20236804%20(2005).pdf"],"categories":["Concepts in physics","Laser science","Electromagnetic radiation","Charge carriers"],"headings":["Introduction","Theory","Rate of spontaneous emission","Radiative and nonradiative decay: the quantum efficiency","See also","References","External links"],"image":["//upload.wikimedia.org/math/9/8/9/9894e1782026d63bc5aa51469b293595.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/c/d/6/cd6c5fa312327dca33de3b38e475deba.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/4/d/1/4d1b7b74aba3cfabd624e898d86b4602.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/4/9/a/49a2b22885b186938408baa5807ca8a9.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/8/a/b/8ab2de96eda14c44facc35e13a2f168e.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/2/5/1/2510c39011c5be704182423e3a695e91.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/7/3/6/7368318dd3647eb6bbf6afaf6d26c48d.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/f/3/f/f3f20e50277a2d8a21bc3c67c4ad040e.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/9/d/f/9dfd055ef1683b053f1b5bf9ed6dbbb4.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/1/14/Spontaneousemission.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/8/d/9/8d9c307cb7f3c4a32822a51922d1ceaa.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/mat